2. Structure of an ANN
An Artificial Neural Network consists of three main layers:

                 Artificial Neural Network
                            │
     ------------------|---------------------------------
      │                    │           │
      ▼                    ▼           ▼
  Input Layer     Hidden Layer        Output Layer

2.1 Input Layer
Definition
The Input Layer is the first layer of an Artificial Neural Network. It receives the input data from the dataset and passes it to the hidden layer. Each neuron in the input layer represents one input feature. The input layer does not perform calculations; it only transfers the information.
Examples
	• Age 
	• Height 
	• Weight 
	• Salary 

2.2 Hidden Layer
Definition
The Hidden Layer is the intermediate layer between the input and output layers. It performs calculations using weights, biases, and activation functions to learn patterns from the data. A neural network may contain one or multiple hidden layers depending on the complexity of the problem.
Examples
	• Pattern Recognition 
	• Feature Extraction 
	• Data Transformation 

2.3 Output Layer
Definition
The Output Layer is the final layer of the neural network. It generates the prediction based on the processed information from the hidden layers. The output can be a class label for classification or a numerical value for regression.
Examples
	• Spam / Not Spam 
	• Disease Positive / Negative 
	• House Price 

