 Feedforward Neural Network (FNN)
A Feedforward Neural Network (FNN) is the simplest type of neural network. Information moves in only one direction, from the input layer to the hidden layer and finally to the output layer. There are no loops or feedback connections. FNN is commonly used for simple classification and regression tasks.
Flowchart

          Feedforward Neural Network
                    │
                    ▼
              Input Layer
                    │
                    ▼
             Hidden Layer
                    │
                    ▼
             Output Layer
Examples
	• Digit Classification 
	• Student Pass/Fail Prediction 
	• Loan Approval 

 Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)

A Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) is an advanced feedforward neural network containing one or more hidden layers. It uses the backpropagation algorithm to adjust weights during training and learn complex patterns. MLP is one of the most commonly used ANN architectures for supervised learning.
Flowchart

           Multi-Layer Perceptron
                    │
                    ▼
             Input Layer
                    │
                    ▼
            Hidden Layer 1
                    │
                    ▼
            Hidden Layer 2
                    │
                    ▼
             Output Layer
Examples
	• Handwritten Digit Recognition 
	• Medical Diagnosis 
	• Credit Risk Prediction 

 Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)
A Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) is a specialized neural network designed for image and video processing. It automatically extracts important features from images using convolution and pooling operations before making predictions. CNN is widely used in computer vision applications because of its high accuracy in recognizing visual patterns.
Flowchart

      Convolutional Neural Network
                 │
                 ▼
          Input Image
                 │
                 ▼
      Convolution Layer
                 │
                 ▼
         Pooling Layer
                 │
                 ▼
     Fully Connected Layer
                 │
                 ▼
         Output Prediction
Examples
	• Face Recognition 
	• Image Classification 
	• Medical Image Analysis 
	• Self-Driving Cars 

 Recurrent Neural Network (RNN)
Definition
A Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) is designed for processing sequential data such as text, speech, and time-series information. Unlike feedforward networks, RNN has feedback connections that allow it to remember information from previous inputs. This memory makes RNN suitable for applications where the order of data is important.
Flowchart

        Recurrent Neural Network
                  │
                  ▼
             Input Data
                  │
                  ▼
          Hidden State Memory
                  │
                  ▼
          Process Next Input
                  │
                  ▼
          Output Prediction
Examples
	• Speech Recognition 
	• Language Translation 
	• Stock Price Prediction 
	• Chatbots 

 Working of ANN
Step 1: Collect the Dataset
Prepare the training dataset with input features and target values.

Step 2: Feed Data into the Input Layer
Each neuron receives one feature from the dataset.

Step 3: Process Data in Hidden Layers
Hidden neurons perform calculations using:
	• Weights 
	• Biases 
	• Activation Functions 

Step 4: Generate Output
The output layer predicts the class label or numerical value.

Step 5: Calculate Error
Compare the predicted output with the actual output.

Step 6: Update Weights
The Backpropagation Algorithm adjusts the weights to reduce prediction errors.

Step 7: Repeat the Process
Training continues for several epochs until the model achieves satisfactory accuracy.

